= Overview =

There is a common assumption that GNU/Linux is a very secure operating system. This is [https://forums.whonix.org/t/fixing-the-desktop-linux-security-model/9172 very far from the truth].

The assumption that free software is inherently more secure than proprietary software is incorrect. Linux is a perfect example of this as it is one of the most popular free software projects yet severely lacking in security.

Free software also does not mean a project cannot be backdoored. There are hundreds of vulnerabilities in the Linux kernel [https://events19.linuxfoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Syzbot-and-the-Tale-of-Thousand-Kernel-Bugs-Dmitry-Vyukov-Google.pdf found each month] and you cannot tell whether they were intentional or not. Backdoors will not be obvious. They will be obscure, easy to miss vulnerabilities.

Proprietary operating systems such as Windows or macOS are far more secure than a standard Linux distribution although sometimes at a forfeit of privacy. Windows and macOS have invested far more work into things such as sandboxing, exploit mitigations and verified boot than Linux. An example of this is Windows 10's Control-Flow Integrity (CFI) implementation, [https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/secbp/control-flow-guard Control-Flow Guard] although CFI is near non-existent on Linux platforms. Another example is macOS's [https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT208330 full verified boot] unlike most Linux distributions which provide an incomplete form covering only the boot chain.

There is more malware available for Windows and macOS but that is due to their larger user base. Relying entirely on security through obscurity by using a less used platform such as Linux is not a good idea.

